i. Background¶

Gold Run culverts were designed for 6" of fill to be added within the culvert spans. The current direction from Boulder County and the relevant permitting agency - Colorado Parks and Wildlife, is to leave the culvert spans unburied and to covert the concrete aprons upstream and downstream of each structure.

Hydraulic factors for retaining full hydraulic capacity of the structures are considered along with the likely persistence of material placed at the upstream and downstream end. This analysis was completed before than final direction, but remains relevant for burying the aprons. Therefore, the assumption is that the culvert aprons experience similar hydraulic conditions at the design flows as the interior of the culvert structures (hopefully a conservative approach).

ii. Methodology¶

A stable reference site was not identified in or near the project area and a pebble count was not conducted pre-project.

This leads to designing a bankfull bed mix from scratch using only the hydraulic parameters of the as-built project. This analysis attempt to create a riprap mix using a variety of guidance documents and the hec-ras outputs of the proposed conditions model.

Guidance from the following agencies were employed:
USACE for d15, d30, and d84 CSU method for d50 UDFCD for reference

Bankfull, 10year, and 25 year event hydraulics were evaluated at the 13 culvert locations in the project. A mix for each event was evaluated. However, given constraints related to culvert conveyance, the bankfull mix was selected. It is understood by all parties that this mix is not stable beyond the 1-2 year range and will likely be washed out of place and potentially replaced by recruitment from upstream areas.

The design mix closely resembled UDFCD's type L riprap, although was smaller at the upper tails of the distribution than the type L spec. Therefore a modified type L riprap mix is suggested for installation on the culvert aprons.

Compute recommended D30 using USACE method¶

In [8]:
# Create dataframe to hold results
sizing = pd.DataFrame(c_data['culvert id'])

# Define gravity constant
accel_gravity = 32.174

sizing['USACE_d30_bkf(in)'] = 12*((1.95 * c_data['culvert_slope']**(0.555)) * (1.25 * c_data['bkf unit discharge'])**(2/3) /  accel_gravity**(1/3))
sizing['USACE_d30_10yr(in)'] = 12*((1.95 * c_data['culvert_slope']**(0.555)) * (1.25 * c_data['10yr unit discharge'])**(2/3) /  accel_gravity**(1/3))
sizing['USACE_d30_25yr(in)'] = 12*((1.95 * c_data['culvert_slope']**(0.555)) * (1.25 * c_data['25yr unit discharge'])**(2/3) /  accel_gravity**(1/3))

# sizing['USACE_d30_25yr(in)'].mean()

Creating material size distribution based on d30:¶

The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers recommends angular rock with a uniform gradation (D85/D15 =2). This material is not preferred for use in a fish-passage structure (see the section on bed porosity, below). An approximate factor to scale D30 of a uniform riprap gradation for one that is appropriate for stream channels is 1.5, so that, D84 = 1.5 * D30, where D84 is the dimension of the intermediate axis of the 84th percentile particle, and similarly for the 30th percentile.

Determine d84 using USACE method¶

In [9]:
sizing['USACE_d84_bkf(in)'] = 1.5 * sizing['USACE_d30_bkf(in)']
sizing['USACE_d84_10yr(in)'] = 1.5 * sizing['USACE_d30_10yr(in)']
sizing['USACE_d84_25yr(in)'] = 1.5 * sizing['USACE_d30_25yr(in)']

Method 2: CSU equations d50¶

Abt, S. R., et al. Development of riprap design criteria by riprap testing in flumes: Phase II, Followup investigations. No. NUREG/CR--4651-VOL. 2. Nuclear Regulatory Commission, 1988. (prepared by S.R. Abt, et al, Colorado State University, 1988).

This method was developed for steep slopes from 2 to 20 percent.

Determine the design unit discharge (eqn 7.1)¶

q' = q * Cf
Where Cf = 1.0 for overland sheet flow,
Cf = 2.0 for a high probability of concentrated flow, and
Cf = 3.0 for a high probability of channelized flow

For culvert fill, assume channelized flow - Cf=3.0

In [10]:
# Create a new dataframe for intermediate calculations of CSU method

csu['CSU_bkf_qprime'] = 3.0 * c_data['bkf unit discharge']
csu['CSU_10yr_qprime'] = 3.0 * c_data['10yr unit discharge']
csu['CSU_25yr_qprime'] = 3.0 * c_data['25yr unit discharge']

Estimate the median stone size (d50) of the riprap layer (eqn 7.2)¶

To size the median stone and prevent stone movement, adjust the design unit discharge by
q* = 1.35 q'

Material sizing method 3: USACE Traditional Ratios d15¶

From U.S. Army Corps of Engineers reference, EM 1110-2-1601, Section e., steep slope riprap design (Corps of Engineers. 1994), section 3-6

Some designers prefer to use the traditional D50 in riprap design. The approximate relationship between D50 and D30 is D50 = D30 (D85/D15)^1/3. Rearrange to d15 = d85 / (d50/d30)^3

Note: working outside of suggested slope limits: Equation 3-3 can be used with either SI (metric) or non-SI units and should be limited to slopes less than 2 percent.

Sizing d15¶

In [14]:
# Bankfull d15
sizing['USACE_d15_bkf(in)'] = sizing['USACE_d84_bkf(in)'] / ((sizing['CSU_d50_bkf(in)'] / sizing['USACE_d30_bkf(in)'])**3) 

# 10yr d15
sizing['USACE_d15_10yr(in)'] = sizing['USACE_d84_10yr(in)'] / ((sizing['CSU_d50_10yr(in)'] / sizing['USACE_d30_10yr(in)'])**3) 

# 25yr d15
sizing['USACE_d15_25yr(in)'] = sizing['USACE_d84_25yr(in)'] / ((sizing['CSU_d50_25yr(in)'] / sizing['USACE_d30_25yr(in)'])**3)

# Plot the mean culvert fill sizing for the job

plt.plot(mean_10yr, color='orange', label='mean 10yr event sizing')
plt.plot(mean_25yr, color='red', label ='mean 25yr event sizing')

# Add labels, title, and legend

plt.xlabel('material class')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.title('Stable culvert fill mixes for 3 design flows - Gold Run')

plt.show()

Given the size constraints of the max culvert fill depth, the plot above indicates the mean 10 yr and mean 25yr riprap sizing will be too large to retain culvert hydraulic capacity. There is some nuance here in that those mixes would likely be washed off the aprons during the critical 100 year event. However, survey of as-built conditions will capture the fill depth on the aprons and modeling will likely assume a static bed shape.

Therefore the mean bankfull event sizing mix will be used here forward.

bkf_designMix = pd.DataFrame(riprap_desc_bkf.loc['mean',:])

# Add column of percent finer than
bkf_designMix['pct_finer'] = [15,30,50,84]

# Add percent of total column
bkf_designMix['% of total'] = 0

# Calculate % of total field
for i in range(len(bkf_designMix)):
    if i == 0:
        bkf_designMix['% of total'].iloc[i] = bkf_designMix['pct_finer'].iloc[i] - 0
    if 4>i>0:
        bkf_designMix['% of total'].iloc[i] = bkf_designMix['pct_finer'].iloc[i] - bkf_designMix['pct_finer'].iloc[i-1]
    if i==4:
        bkf_designMix['% of total'].iloc[i] = 100 - (bkf_designMix['pct_finer'].iloc[i])

E. Evaluating bankfull design mix¶

Hydraulic considerations and the original culvert designs limit the final depth of riprap on aprons. A riprap mix that is stable at bankfull is likely the largest mix that can be used while attaining hydraulic capacity. The histogram of the bankfull mix is below

Interpolate the UDFCD sizes to match design percentile (quantile) classes¶

In [89]:
# Interpolate the missing percentiles values in UDFCD to match design mix percentiles
# https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.14.0/reference/generated/numpy.interp.html

udfcd_vals = 1.0*(np.sort(typeL['udfcd_sizing(in)']))
# print (udfcd_vals)

udfcd_interp_vals = np.interp(design_ptiles, udfcd_ptiles, udfcd_vals)
print ("UDFCD interpolated sizes:", udfcd_interp_vals)

UDFCD interpolated sizes: [  3.75   6.     9.    13.4 ]

This comparison indicates the two distributions are nearly identical up to the d50 size. However, the UDFCD type L riprap has a larger d84 than calculated for the design mix (13.4 inches vs. 9.6 inches).

Calculate Fill Depth based on d50¶

In [91]:

convervative fill depth:  17.8854729852
In [92]:
# USACE method: 1.5 * d50
depth_USACE = 1.5 * bkf_designMix['mean'].loc['d50']
print ('USACE fill depth: ', depth_USACE)

USACE fill depth:  13.4141047389

Both calculated fill depths are greater than the design fill depth of the culverts. However, the aprons are wider than the boxes. As well, the channel was originally supposed to slope into and out of the box between the wingwalls (as opposed to being flat such as the new concrete aprons were generally constructed). This allows SOME flexibility with fill depths greater than 6". However, 6" max fill depth at the culvert inlets/outlets is still important for the modeling of as-built conditions.
